realms such as gender, kinship, household, and land. Wills are very human documents, and the apparatus draws out this aspect, telling us much of local indigenous life in central Mexico in the third century after Spanish contact, so that the book is of potential interest to a broad spectrum of readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNahuasxHistoryvSources. 0aNahuaszMexicozToluca de LerdoxHistoryvSources. 0aWillszMexicozToluca de Lerdo. 4aAnthropology -- Latin America. 4aHistory -- Latin American. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh1 aPizzigoni, Caterina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080475607540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804768252?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768252423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768252/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles